history.prompt: Explain why the sky is blue
history.response:
Hello there, friend! I'd be happy to tell you about why we see blue sky! 

Blue sky isn't just blue because of blue pigment - it's actually because of something amazing called "Rayleigh scattering! 

Blue light (which we can't see) is made up of really tiny particles in the air called molecules and particles of nitrogen and oxygen. When sunlight comes through those particles, blue light gets scattered more than red light because blue is smaller than red. That's why we see blue everywhere! 

Blue sky also looks blue because of how much blue light reaches our eyes - we don't see red light from space because it got too far away. Blue just happens to be the color that travels farther! 

Blue sky isn't just blue, though - it changes too! During sunrise and sunset, we see red because of particles in the atmosphere too. And at night, we see stars because they're actually blue too, but we can't see them because of blue sky! 

Blue sky isn't just blue, it's actually really cool science! Blue sky shows us how amazing our planet works!
